'''Delayed judgment''' is a [[Keyword (linguistics)|keyword]] mentioned in [[Sean Covey|Sean Covey's]] [[self-help]] book, ''[[The 7 Habits of Highly Effective Teens]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Covey|first=Sean|title=The 7 Habits of Highly Effective Teens|year=1998|publisher=Fireside|location=New York, NY 10020|isbn=0-684-85609-3|pages=16–18}}</ref> Referring to the our [[paradigm]]s of other people and situations, delayed judgment is a tool that can be used to make our paradigms more accurate.
"We too often judge people without having all of the facts... Out paradigms are often incomplete, inaccurate or completely messed up. Therefore, we shouldn't be so quick to judge."

